Command: python3 -m unittest quality.test_regression.CodeReviewRegressionTests.test_bug_011_citation_verifier_rejects_out_of_root_paths

unittest reports the test as `expected failure` because the regression
test is decorated with @unittest.expectedFailure. The underlying
assertion `self.assertFalse(result.ok, ...)` raises AssertionError on
unpatched code because `verify_citation()` returns ok=True for both the
absolute-path and `..`-traversal source_path inputs — the verifier
computes `Path(root) / source_path`, calls `read_bytes()` against the
out-of-root file, runs `extract_excerpt(..., line=1)` against the
out-of-root content, and returns `VerificationResult(ok=True,
excerpt='alpha', warnings=())`. The fact that an out-of-root file is
read is the bug; the regression test asserts the verifier should refuse
to do so.

Reproduction (reduced):

    >>> from bin import citation_verifier
    >>> from pathlib import Path
    >>> import tempfile
    >>> with tempfile.TemporaryDirectory() as outside, tempfile.TemporaryDirectory() as repo:
    ...     sentinel = Path(outside) / "secret.txt"
    ...     sentinel.write_text("alpha\nbeta\ngamma\n")
    ...     citation = {"document": str(sentinel), "line": 1}
    ...     formal_doc = {"source_path": str(sentinel)}
    ...     result = citation_verifier.verify_citation(citation, formal_doc, Path(repo))
    ...     print(result.ok, repr(result.excerpt))
    True 'alpha'

The test fails on unpatched code; it will pass once `verify_citation()`
gains a containment check that rejects `source_path` values whose
resolved location is not relative to `Path(root).resolve()`.

unittest output (with @unittest.expectedFailure):

